text: Aroma is rather mild, spicy, rye is noticeable, hoppy in an earthy and herbal way. Light-medium mouthfeel. Flavour is tofee, rye gives it a nice spicy feel though. Hops is very nice and beer is quite bitter, with a medium long , full of pine and earthy green hops but beautifully balanced with the malt base.cool one.
Pours dark red qith medium white head. Aroma is rye, bitter, some caramel, light dust. Taste is bitter, rye, caramel, some cookies, light bread, some metal. Nice beer!

Red color, small head. Aroma of fresh berries, lots of caramel, hops, hints of alcohol. Taste: sweetish-bitter, intense flavour of berries, some roast, crisp, hoppy finish. Medium plus body. Above avg carbo.

Backlog

Taste is also caramel, hops, spicy and quite refreshing with a nice bitterness.

Can shared. Pours dark amber with rich off-white head, medium body, good lacing, dry bitter finish and strong bitter aftertaste. Resin, citrus peel hops along with caramel, roasted malts, toffee. A very balanced, very intense, rich and surprising IPA. Take it slow, and let it reveal its magic. Great!

Strong, rich caramel backbone with hints of chocolate, combined with pine medium bitterness, smooth, nice buildup.

First bottle of the new year! Pours dark red with little head. Aroma is rather mild, spicy, rye is noticeable, hoppy in an earthy and herbal way. Deep and even a bit boozy aroma. Light-medium mouthfeel. Flavour is also rather mild, rye gives it a nice spicy feel though. Hops is very nice and beer is quite bitter, with a medium long finish which is my favourite part, full of pine and earthy hops but beautifully balanced with the malt base.
a strong hoppy aroma, with pine and some spiciness. a robust flavor with some maltiness and a toffee flavor. well done.

Keg Third of a Pint at BrewDog, Shepherds Bush, London in Jan 2016 - Deep Reddish Brown in colour. Average creamy off-white head. Malty; toasty grainy rye malts, caramel, toffee. Spicy; peppery. Fruity; orange and grapefruit citrus. Hoppy; piney resinous hops. Good malt/fruit/hop balance. Bittersweet. Grainy spicy malts meet citrus fruits and piney hops. Very drinkable. Enjoyed this. Nice Rye IPA! (2016-01-04)
A very fruity/hoppy aroma, small head and clear brown head color, bitter start to finish.
Pours red with a nice beige head, aroma of fruits, caramel, toffee, hops, flavor is bitter and sweet with caramel, toasted bread, rye, tangerine, medium bodied, nice

20-12-16 // can. Pours a brownish beer with a small head.Nose is hoppy. Taste is well balalnced between sweet malts, some caramel and toffee and a strong hop bitterness with grapefruit and citrus flavors. Nice rye smoothness. Bitter finish.

Can, 330ml. Pours dark reddish-brown, tall, thick off white head. Strong scent of hops, grapefruit and malt. Mouth feel is medium thick, slightly oily and gently carbonation. Ends slightly sticky, maly and flavorful.

Can from BrewDog website. Awesome name and can art. Quite red looking, on the red side of ruddy brown, white foam. Superb tasty stuff, spicy and sweet malts, toffee, dulce de leche, then a big resiny citrusy hop crunch. Bitter finish, long. Really nice trade-off for the sweet malt and bitter hop.
Can from Beer Cartel 300816. Thus is a malty IPA that closely resembles an amber ale. While it is not the best looking beer going round it is super malty one of BrewDogs finest.
Dark red with big redish brown foam. Light hoppy aroma of red fruits. Bittersweet taste with hops citrus and sweet red fruits like strawberry.
Brilliant beer. One of the best beers from Brewdog. The rye adds a nice spiciness.

Can from appellation wines dalry road. Pours slightly hazy rust orange. Intense nose of mango, pine resin, raisins, forest floor. Taste is quite sweet, lots of hops, big mix of different hop characters. Nice.
Big citrus pine aroma in a copper brown pour. Big flavours to match with hops and fruity caramel malt in perfect balance before giving way to an excellently sustained bitter finish.

Aroma is slight dusty grains, deep malty, hoppy citrus notes and pine. Taste is a little bit too much towards the malty side, but it brings some of the rye notes I was expecting - slight spice, piney and grapefruit bitterness. A wee note of licorice as well, believe it or not. This beer almost brings it all the way, it¬ís a little thin "in the middle". Overall though a good rye IPA

pours dark amber, clear, with beige/yellow one finger tan head. Visually medium carbonation. Aroma: slightly spicy, grain malt aroma, with notes of toffee hint of caramel, and intense hop aroma, which takes on pine, citruses. flavor: rich grain malt flavor, with notes of toffee, hint of honey, caramel, coffee, well balanced with hop flavor, which takes on citruses, pine, with some spicy tones. 33cl can. Clear reddish brown colour with a nice tan head. Hay, grainy, caramel, toasted malts and light pine in the aroma. Average carbonation and medium body. Taste is bitter with citrus and spicy notes. Overall, a nice beer.

Red rye IPA by BrewDog, can from De Caigny. Lightly lacing, creamy, dense, regulary shaped, pale yellowish beige head on top of a deep and warm vermillion red-hued copper beer, clear but with disperse darker yeast dots throughout - so minute that they are barely visible to the naked eye, but rendering it equally (yet only lightly) misty with the sediment added. Lovely bouquet of pink grapefruit flesh, biscuit, tangerine, marmelade, cedar needles, black pepper, spareribs, bitter honey, hemp and dried mushrooms. Lively onset, fruity hints of redcurrant and mandarin with light dried mushroom-like umami hint and hop bitterness already manifesting itself from the start; medium carbo, full but smooth and slick, bit resinous mouthfeel. Pleasantly biscuity malt middle with a soft toasted edge and paired with the expected soft spicy hint of rye (as in moist rye bread), supporting a very hoppy, long, drying finish bringing tonic water- and strongly grapefruit-like bitterness as well as a wave of retronasal citrusy, piney and spicy (even very slightly minty) aromas; malt bittersweet accent goes down into the throat along with this generous amount of hops and leaves one completely satisfied. This is another BrewDog beauty, rich and opulent in its hoppiness but well balanced with a bittersweet malt body which leaves enough room for the rye to shine through as well.

Nice mix of copper/amber with a decent tan head. Toffee, slight cherry, raisins and spiced apple on the nose. Ever so slight alcohol taste, toffee and port flavours - pine hop flavours with some rye spiciness. Medium bodied with gentle carbonation and a smooth as all hell mouthfeel. (14.5)

33cl can at home from Brewdog webshop. Nose is floral. Body is clear deep amber brown, head is big, beige, creamy, mostly lasting, excellent lacing. Aroma is caramel, milk chocolate, wood, spices, tobacco, leaves, tea, dried fruits. Light sweet, medium bitter, hint of fruity sour. Finish is long lasting roasty medium bitter, light umami, later rather hoppy bitter. Medium to full body, oily texture, average carbonation. Quite easy dessert beer, interesting, nice one.

Can from Boxbeers. Hazy brown with a lasting off-white head. Aroma is sweet, malty, caramel, rye and moderate hoppy - citrus. Flavor is quite sweet and rather bitter. Dry and rather bitter finish. 280616

Can from Brewdog Brussels. Pours ruddy copper with a beige head. Aroma is sort of spicy, hoppy malty. Med body or so. Flavor has a sort of burnt rubber aspect, but the hop crazy and the rye spicy really make that work. Love rye. Not strongly bitter, and the flavor is quite a mix, but lots of hop and rye make anything work.

Can from Brewdog Brussels. Pours amber with a thick beige head and a roasted toffee aroma. There is a medium-bodied roasted malt flacor with a little chocolate and a dry pine-like finish. The hop profile is quite interesting and goes well with the rye.

A really nice a tasty hoppy red ale. Nice for late evenings.Lovely clear amber color with a thick tan head. Good lacing. Nice intensity in the aroma. Medium to full body and pleasant soft-ish carbonation. Just a little bit to sweet to be perfect in my book. Oily texture. Can at BrewDog Brussels. Pours clear dark amber with a medium, frothy beige head, medium retention with good lacing. Aroma is spicy and earthy rye malt, moderate earthy and herbal hops. Flavor is moderate herbal and spicy hops and bitterness with spicy rye malt and a dry finish. Medium body and carbonation.
Clear, red amber with thick light beige froth. Pine and caramel aroma. Flavour has hoppy bitterness, pine and stone fruit. Some caramel as well. Well balanced and tasty.

Great brew.

Wohooo, wtf was this? Brewdog contiunues with it¬ís creativity and interesting recipes. As they say on can, this is red rye ipa, but, maybe little bit more red and rye than ipa. Beautiful long, long biter aftertaste, so much caramel and spices. Citrus hops are also there. Very, very interesting brew. I¬íll drink this again, for sure.

33cl can. Pours clear dark amber colour with a mid-sized good lasting beige head. Aroma of intense bitter hops, spruce, red fruits. Taste of dark malt, intense bitter hops, red malt, spruce, nuts, long bitter finish.

A 330ml can with a best before date of 16th December 2016 and poured into a Spiegelau IPA glass. It poured a very nice clear dark amber colour with a two finger beige head that had good retention and left nice lacing. Nice tropical aromas of mango and pineapple with a hint of caramel, spice and alcohol. Tastes of some light but sweet mango mixed in with toasty bread graininess and a long lasting piney grapefruit pith bitter finish. Medium bodied with light carbonation. Overall this was only ok for me. Looks and smells great but I thought that the taste was a bit light (cancelled each other out) with too much grain and pith and not enough fruit.
Overall: Pepper, sweet toffee, bread.Note: Can 330 ml at a De Klomp tasting. Reviewed 2016-05-14.

Can at home. It pours clear ruby brown with a bubbly off white head. Fruity hoppy and toasted malty aroma. Bread and light citrus. Sweet nuts. Toasted malty. Bready and piney hoppy. Lingering bitter finish. Tasty stuff.

Can. Clear amber with an inch of beige head. Rich spiced toffee aroma with some cocoa and kumquats, slight mango. Not totally my sort of thing but very well put together.
Can. Clear, amber, minimal head, white foam, medium bitterness, light sweetness, medium body, thin feel, average carbonation, & bitter finish.
Can. Beautiful clear amber color with nice beige head. Aroma is mango, some rye spiciness. Taste is sweet mango, toasted malts, caramel, pines. Bittersweet finish. Soft carbonation. Good stuff.

Light to moderate sweet taste with a pretty heavy bitter long-lasting finish. Mid-bodied with a soft carbonation. Brilliant!

33 cl can. Dark mahogany colour, tan head, lots of carbonation. Aroma is well balanced of hops and malts. Mouthfeel is sticky and dry. Flavours of caramel and toffee, short spicy peppery aftertaste.

Can. An amber colored beer, hazy, and with a dense, finger-thick light beige head. Spiced, caramel-ish, bread-ish aroma with pine cones, resins, some orange zest and a peppery rye touch. Can 330ml @ Sommerhuset
Pours amber with a beige head. Aroma has notes of malt, caramel, rye, citrus, grape and pine. Taste is medium sweet and medium bitter with a long piney. citrus, grapefruit and rye finish. Body is medium to full, texture is oily, carbonation is soft.

330ml can from SIP, Tallinn. BBE 16/12/16. Pours dark reddish orange with a smooth white head. Aroma of caramely malts, crisp biscuity notes, grassy and herbal hops, hints of rye and citrus. Can from Booths, Media City. Deep amber coloured with next to no head. It has potent sweet and grainy malts, fused with a tropical fruitiness which carries to its taste, here a small spiciness exists.
Can. An amber beer with a lazing yellowish head. The aroma has notes of citrusy hops, malt, and caramel. The flavor is sweet with notes of caramel, hops, and citrusy hops, leading to a bitter finish.

33 cl. can. Dark amber colour with a small off-white head. Aroma and flavour of malt, fruit, hops, spice, yeast, resin and rye.
Pours dirty brown with a slight brown head. Aroma is rye and straw. Taste is caramel sweet, earthy, moderate bitterness, malt sweetness.

Can. Dark red-brown. Smells of toast in a pine forest. Tastes of caramel, toast, rye spiciness, hint of wood and vanilla, pine and grapefruit. Fairly resinous and dank

Can from Real Ale Store, Newark. Rich ruby red colour with a thick white head. Aroma citrus hoppy, orange marmalade. Taste marmalade sweet with a mid bitter finish.
Caramel, malt, rye, a touch of ginger and spice, lingering taste. I m becoming a fan of rye!

ON can from Vinmonopolet NOrway, on order. AMber color, good foam. Medium/high aroma intensity; hops, malt, light pine, citrus and caramel. Medium body & complexity. Some light immediate sweetness, but bitterness balances well. Very enjoyable

CAN 33 CL. Clear dark rich ruby, creamy beige head - a great look. Taste: moderate juicy sweetness, berries, in balance with a piney and zesty bitterness. Not sure I am able to find the rye here. Overall, a yummy and juicy red IPA.

Can from O¬íBrien¬ís, Athlone [110316]

Can, 7.4%. Clear dark amber/brown with medium tan head. Aroma is malt, caramel, hops, fruit, rye, grapefruit and pine. Flavour is malt, caramel, rye, grapefruit, pine, medium sweet, little marmalade and medium bitter.
Can 330ml. Copper red, thin white head with medium lacing. Soft carbonation. Toffee and pine. Plenty of hoppy bitterness and malty notes.

Can, Belgrade-Serbia. Semi clear dark red pour, off white head. Nose: caramel, caramelized onions, citrus. Mouth: Amber, orange juice, clean.

Can. Clear amber beer, medium off-white head. Nose is hoppy, citrus, grapefruit pith, pine, malt is somewhere in the background. Flavor is pine, pineapple, mango, pithy bitterness, soft malts. Can hardly pick out any rye here. Overall - it¬ís a brewdogy Brewdog IPA.
One of the best IPA whenever I tasted. Hoppy aroma, balanced bitterness and smooth creamy and really long finish. Grate job!

1/2 Pint on tap @ Barcelona Beer Festival. Amber colour with beige head. Aroma is mango, orange and tangerine. From the first sniff, they nailed it with the label - it smells red, it smells rye, it smells a bit IPA. Thar¬ís kinda nice, worth 6, but after the first sniff, it gets the APA yeast messiness. Ugh.

Can (from UJH, Tallinn), BB 16.12.2016. Pours clean brownish copper with beige head. The head stays. Aroma is sweet, malt, rye, caramel. Can from Gasthaus Schiffer: Brown, light reddish color, light brownish head. Aroma is nice hoppy with pine, grapefruite, citrus peel and tropical fruits. Great Beer.

Pours dark brown, with a slight head. Flavours of hops and malts. Initial slight sweetness, with zesty tones. Definitely worth a try.

Tasted from the tap on the 04/03/2016 at the Brewdog Bar BCN. Clear copper colour with a creamy tan head. Aroma has pine, caramel, bread, some grapefruit and florals. Taste has caramel, grapefruit and malts. Next one please!

330ml can from somewhere. Pours deep brown, off-white head. Taste presents quite a dry rye, smooth with some spice but ultimately lacking in earthy layered flavours and depth. Bit disappointing for me chaps.

Clear, copper colored, medium- offwhite head. Aroma is quite hoppy, floral-pine and citrus mostly, some caramel and bit toasty. Taste is medium sweet toffee and caramel malt, light rye, medium+ hoppy aroma, floral-pine and grapefruit, medium bitterness, dry finish but still some sweetness. Medium bodied, soft carbonation, resiny. 
(can, Bierhalle Deconinck, Vichte)

330 ml. can @ Brewdog Brussels. Yes I got this one exclusively because of the name! Bottom of the can says 16.12.16 & ¬ìBloodless Killer¬î. Dark red copper amber, tanned bubbles. Nose is thick chewy herbal & pine hops, thick jam-like base, candy, grapefruit, herbal & pine qualities are thick & heavy. Taste is herbal dark red fruit, big hops, jam mixed with pine resin, herbal hops & caramel, goop, grapefruit, jam. Thick herbal sludgy jam body. Successful use of the BrewDog hop profile, works well with the thick body. I have also grown towards these guys with time. Very solid & successful BrewDog beer.

Can. Clear deep amber colour. Absolutely delicious. Brutal bitterness yet subtly balanced by deep caramelly malty notes. Citrusy grapefruity zesty hops flavour, also intense aroma. Great. Long lasting dry hoppy finish urging you to drink more. Simple but excellent.

Can kindly shared by lukka19, many thanks.  Amber color with medium off-white head. Strong citrus hoppy aroma with zest, pines. Strong citrus hoppy aroma with herbal notes, spices, zest. Solid caramel malty taste. Very good.

Can. Brown hazy color with minimum white head. Aroma of hops, citrus fruits, zest, pines, some wheaty notes, caramel, floral notes. Taste is nice citrusy, zesty, piney, toffee, nice hoppy bitter, very good
Can by lukka19, many thanks. Pours deep amber color, lightly beige head. Aroma of floral hops, caramel, malt. Taste is bitter, floral hoppy, caramel, rye, alcohol is present.
Can shared with Ashton McCobb. Pours clear dark copper with a thick white head. Aromas of citrus hops, slightly earthy. Taste is earthy, bitter, spice. Tangy, dry finish. Easy drinking too.

Can.
Appearance - deep red to brown. Nice fluffy head. 
Nose - toffee, oranges, spice.
Taste - oranges again, some spice. Earthy, maybe root vegetables. 
Palate - close to medium bodied with a creamy texture and a long dry finish.
Overall - hops dominate the rye a bit. Lovely beer though.

Can, many thanks to Leighton. Pours deep red copper with off white head. Aroma is mango, citrus, grain, rye, malt, caramel. Flavor is dry, pine, citrus, mango, rye, earth. Bordering on being a bit big / bold, but remains exceptionally well balanced & interesting.

330 ml can at home. Clear dark amber copper color with red notes and light beige head. Aroma is hoppy and malty, pine, grapefruit, grassy, rye notes, light bread, caramel. Sweet and biter like aroma with the addition of some red fruity notes - berries. Medium oily body with soft carbonation.

From O¬íBrien¬ís in Dun Laoghaire. Appearance: Dark ruby red, medium off white head. Aroma: Toffee and rye, lovely citra notes coming through too, smells wonderful. Flavour: Wonderful rye flavour, citra hops shining through with a big caramel/toasty thump, zingy hoppy finish, lovely.

Pours copper to brown with quick disappearing head with mild carbonation. 

Beer was a little too cold as the aroma was quite mild until it warmed up a little and then started to come alive. 

There¬ís dark caramel, lemon, lime, orange peel, pine, wood and raisin. The taste is quite bitter, with sweetness later and a nice medium to long finish and a hint of booze right at the end, although less than you¬íd expect given the 7%.

Was expecting more pronounced rye and hop flavours - usual Brewdog over-hyping (if you call it squid assassin, then you expect something pretty punchy!) - but it¬ís a good beer nonetheless.
Ruby colour, off white head. Aroma of bread, rosemary, caramel, licorice and earthy hops. Taste is light sweet, dry finish, spicy flavour. Medium body, oily texture, soft carbonation.

Can from mchughs. Pours brownish really with little or no head. Pine, resin, wood, earth, rye nose. Fruit Forrest, nut, wood, toffee flavor. Light mouthful with a strong bitter finish. Thought it lack a little balance on malts. Fairly decent overall.

How : tap Appearance : almost clear deep amber, medium to small slightly tanned head. Aroma : grapefruit, caramel, floral, herbs, stone fruits and some red berries. Palate : medium body, average carbonation.

Can from Offie and Toffee, Bethnal Green. Solid RIPA. Burnt toffee and toast, with wintry berry fruitiness. Pretty sweet. I learn as I grow. I have learnt this week, that I would rather a BIPA than a RIPA.

Can. Pours is clear amber with thich beige head. Aroma of pine, resin, fruity, caramel, tea amd cocoa. Solid malty base, cocoa and chocolate mouthfeel, light sweet, light to moderate bitter. Medium to heavy body, oily texture, soft carbonation, long bitter finish. This one is pretty extraordinary, well done.

330ml Can from Brewdog¬ís DogHouse BottleDog, Glasgow (¬£3.00):
A pretty good offering, it did start fairly average but improved plenty as things went on; the taste in particular being a good one with plenty bitterness with grain, rye & tropical fruits coming through strong. It seemed more American IPA than rye beer but I enjoyed it anyway with lots of fruits & floral touches that came with a nice alcohol kick too.

Can. Pours in chopper clean body with medium creamy head. Aroma has caramel character, floral, light citrus. Taste has dry toffee, almost biscuit, sweetness with high earthy bitterness. Body is full, medium carbonation.

Pours deep copper with medium tan head. Nose is piney and tropical fruits. Aromas are pine resin, citrus. Average carbonation, light body. Medium bitter and piney finish.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

330ml bottle from Hoptimism. 
Thin off white head, good lacing. Dark reddish amber body. Nose is caramel, a little spice. Flavour is sweet caramel, rye spice, treacle, grassy bitter finish with some spice. Great mouthfeel, light carbonation with plenty of chew. One of the best rye beers I've tasted.
Draught at Bierhaus. A ruby-copper pour with decent lacing. Grapefruit hop aroma with a bunch of rye. Nicely dry with a surprisingly light citrus finish. Long aftertaste.
Can in Brewdog Newcastle. Ruby with a thin cream head. Mild pine aroma. The taste is spicy with aniseed, stewed fruits and plenty of pine hop. Good stuff.

0,33 l can 
red, slightly hazy, frothy, tan foam, spruce, citrus, cereal, medium sweetness, medium bitterness, medium body, oily feel, slick feel, soft carbonation, long finish,

11.02.2016, tap @ UNA:
Tiny shortlasting head. Aroma is slightly fresh, leafs, hops, rubber, rye, grass, weeds, hops, bark, minerals, grass, moss. Taste is slightly harsh boozy, weeds, paper, booze, rye, burnt grain, harsh grass, bark, soil, almond essence. Medium to longlasting bitterness, harsh boozy mouthfeel. Meh!

330 ml can from BeerLovers Vienna, bb 16/12/16.
Deep copper, clear body, with a medium, creamy, lacing, beige head.
Aroma of grapefruit, grass, rye, passion fruit, orange, resin, flowers, caramel.
Taste follows this, with some more herbal notes.
Medium, slick mouthfeel, with an average carbonation.
Finishes bitter, medium dry, zesty, grassy, piney, with rye and some fruits.

Nice one, although I was expecting a bit more maybe. I don¬ít like the grassy notes too much, but the fruit notes are nice. Overall still an enjoyable IPA, but I¬íve had better ones from BrewDog.

Can 33cl / Lata 33cl.
@ XXXII The Great Power of Beer & Wine, Sevilla, Espa√±a.
A: Dark amber / Ambar oscuro.
T/S: Hops, resinous, slightly fruity / Lupulo, resinoso, ligeramente afrutado.

Can. Pours pours a cloudy reddish amber with a thin lasting off white head. Aroma of caramel, pine, toffee, spice, earthy. Taste is of red fruits, strawberries, pine, spice, toffee, burnt finish. Soft, foamy to oily mouthfeel, medium carbonation.
can ambrato carico buona schiuma fine persistente buon naso agrumato leggero resinoso agrume buon maltato in bocca secchezza media buon amaro un filo pepato

Canned, 330 ml.
Clear copper colour, ceamy and stabile tan head, which remains finger thick.
Nose brings pine, caramel, bread...
Aroma contains the same combined with some grapefruit and florals. Slick to oily feel.
Warming, lingering bittersweet finish with nuts and resin.
Balanced, very enjoyable.
Can at home. Deep reddish brown with a beige head. Toasted grain and light caramel notes with some squid spice. Medium body. Good stuff.

Can. Beer Stop, Dronfield. Clear, copper red. Foamy, sticky, off white head. Nose has juicy, jammy, rye spice. Brewdog toffee malts. It actually smells like a beefed up version of the Punk I¬íve just had. Taste is jammy sweet. Light bitter. Some dryness. Palate is light, to the point of feeling thin. Spicy bitter finish. Can¬ít help comparing it to the Kernel red rye IPA, against which this falls short. Smells great, mind you.
Can. this has great fruity hop characteristics, backed up by a clean malt influence, nice hop bitterness on the finish.

Can from Cornelius. Pours clear ruby. Nose is fruity and hoppy, rye and bready malts, toasted malts, caramel, citrus, resin. Taste is caramel and toffee, citrus and resinous hops, medium sweetness, pine, light stickiness. Underneath the nonsense name etc actually lies very solid beer.

330ml bottle at home in Richmond as ¬íBrewDog Albino Squid Assassin¬í, 7.4%, BB Dec 2016. "Bloodless Killer" printed on bottom of can. Nice artwork - not Brewdog¬ís usual style. A deep cherry red, clear, sparkling, creamy beige head leaves full lacing. Aroma is wafer, rose petal, dried out zest, a touch earthy. Body is a little foamy, tingly carbonation. Taste is mint, booze, pretty dry, gin, peppery, some citrus. I like dry, spicy, hoppy beers although this one is maybe a touch too dry and boozy. Still, pretty nice.

18th January 2015Can. Clear amber beer, good cream colour head. Palate is light, mildly dry. Decent fine carbonation. Smooth malts, mild to medium rye tang and spice. Light but juicy pine hop, very mild skunk. A light touch of sweetish marmalade and red berries. Soft juicy and spicy. Very drinkable.
Can at home. Pours deep ruby amber, nose is caramel, toffee, pine, taste is similar, dry.

Draught at Brewdog Bar, G√∂teborg. Dark copper/orange beer with a nice lasting offwhite/beige head. Hoppy citrus and pine aroma, hay, rye bread, some caramel. 

Hoppy ryebread flavor, citrus, grapes, some berries. Ok.

Can shared by Mick. Albino Squid Assassin 7.4%

A deep Amber red with a big drank citrusy hop bouquet. Bitter pine, very dank with little citrus and rye spice but nicely balanced. Good beer with a great can.

Can from Brewdog headquarters Ellon, pours a ruby red/brown with a small off white head. Aroma of pomegranate, berry jam with hints of pine and caramel. Flavour is earthy and dry with hints of orange peel and a pine hop finish. Excellent beer.
Can at BrewDog Clerkenwell. Clear dark red brown lasting beige head. Rich malty. Good malts good hops. Hops are very good so is the balance. Very likeable.

Can from Brewdog online. Deep reddish brown colour with a creamy off-white head. Aroma is grapefruit, hops, pine and sweet caramel malt. Taste is sweet and malty then pine, hoppy bitterness. Some nice sticky sweetness in the finish and a touch of late alcohol warmth. Medium body, lowish carbonation. Like it, very nice.
1/3 pint on tap @ Brewdog Helsinki. Pours deep clear amber with a low head. Aroma fruity and piney malts. Flavor is robust malts, pine, fruits and hops. Great balance. Creamy. Good.
can. Copper with thin white head. Grapefuit, bread, pine aroma. Sweet malt flavour with smooth hoppy bitterness

Brown, dark anber clear. Malty, ryish pine on nose. Med full bldied, really nice soft palateable bitters, some chewyness. Pines, some forestyness. Easy drink. Just nice caramel sweets, pines, the rye pushing a slight sticky body.-- bb
Interesting mix. Strongly hopped but with good malt backbone. Background sweetness like a good DIPA. Very nice.
Tap at Brewdog Helsinki, Helsinki. Colour is clear orange with small white head. Aromas and flavours: Sweetness, caramel, grain, hops, some fruits and malts.

Beautiful little takeout tin from Leicester Bottledog. Clear red speckling with beige. Nice peppery red berry, peachy vomit, grenadine, dank pollen, dark bread nose. Too hot peppery booze taste with alcohol slightly dominating cherry lolly and grenadine fruit. Deep Heat. Smells better than it tastes.

33cl can at BS Shoreditch, London. It pours a clean copper color with a large off white head. Aroma is sweet hoppy with spices herbal notes dried leaves honey melon and apricots. Taste is also medium sweet and lightly dry and grassy spicy with notes I herbs honey melon apricots rye bread zesty citrus. Medium bodied with good carbonation. Overall, real tasty

Pours clear deep copper with two fingers of off-white head. Aroma of perfume, light alcohol, resin, grapefruit. Taste is initially light sweet followed by a rich resinous bitter finish. Medium full and smooth body with soft carbonation.

Fancy Can. Dark amber with off white head. Piney aroma, caramel, toffee, some grapefruits. Taste is well balanced, caramel, pine and grapefruits with a pleasant spicy rye flavour finish. Full bodied with a clean slightly bitter finish. A solid enjoyable beverage.

Can courtesy of Geraint and Helen ( cheers you two!) consumed at home Thursday 21st January 2016   Pours amber/reddy colour with an off-white head. Hoppy but with some bitter toffee elements, streaky, fresh zippy, green, zappy hops but carried on a layer of sweet maltiness.I likes it. A7 A4 T8 P3 Ov15 3.8
Bevuta in lattina. Comprata a lo sfuso a torino. Bel colore ambrato scuro. Schiuma abbondante e mediamente persistente. Buona luppolatura. Finale scrimancitico.

33cl can. Poured mahogany color with a thin white head. Caramel malty, hoppy, citrusy fruity notes. Caramel dominating but not that sweet. Flavor has caramel, nuts, (could be the rye here as well), citrus fruits, long slightly bitter finish.
bottle at home from brewdog onlinebig, pithy full bodied, sticky, rye, red berries, citrus, juicy, complex malt with plenty of hops to balance

Pours a deep copper with a very short lived head. The aroma is a very berry delight. It has the taste of most brewdog red/dark IPA¬ís but that¬ís not a bad thing, lots of nice red berry flavours are balanced out by a great bitterness.
330ml can from BrewDog Doghouse. Chestnut brown, big foamy head. Resin grain malt aroma. Spicy rye grain toffee malt flavour. Sharp with bitter aftertaste.Unusual and distinctive.
Can mail order from brewdog. Good drop. Great appearance. Nice can. Smells better than it tastes but it tastes good

Can from Bottle Baron. Clear ruby/brown body with a medium off-white head. Low carbonation. Faint lacing. Aroma of raspberry syrup, blood orange and caramel. Flavour of pineapple, toffee and a dry, hoppy finish. Medium body with an oily mouthfeel. Light fizz. BrewDog have released a few gems recently - this is one of them.

Keg at Brewdog Shepherds Bush, London. An amber/brown coloured pour with a thin off white head on top. Fruity, malty, caramel aroma. Tastes similar, fruity, malty, caramel, rye with some grapefruit in there too. Nice one from Brewdog.
Can at home, 8th January 16. Pours reddish, slight head. Aroma is grainy hops, some fruity notes. Taste is malty, good grain, pine hops. Pretty tasty

330ml can from Brewdog online store. Red-amber colour, foamy beige head leaving lacing and aroma of rye grain, hoppy, citrus & pine. Flavour is malt, grain, rye, slight roasted note, sweetish with fruity hops, grapefruit, pine, and tangy spicy bitterness. Smooth mouthfeel, medium bodied, soft carbonation, dry earthy spicy bitter finish. Nicely drinkable.
7.5abv keg at brewdog Edinburgh... Deep red copper .. Thin white lacing... Soft sweet toffee fruit... Sticky toffee fruit.. Soft woody malts..
From a can, this has great fruity hop characteristics, backed up by a clean malt influence, nice hop bitterness on the finish.

Clear brown-amber beer with a thick off-white head and a light, hoppy aroma. Because there are a number of hops used none in particular jump out. So it¬ís a fruity, hoppy blend that is nicely balanced. There¬ís an airy, floral edge to it as well which I didn¬ít expect and which dominates the aftertaste. Crisp and refreshing, it¬íd be perfect for nursing on a hot day if you¬íve got it chilled enough.

33cl can from bottledog brought by a friend. Color is dark copper to brown. Head is medium and persistent. Medium bitterness. Low sweentness. Nice long and dry finish. Aroma is super malty, caramel, roasted, hoppy, squid?, resin, piney, fruity.

Can in Gabrovo, Bulgaria - picked up at BottleDog London. Pours clear copper-gold with a frothy off-white head. Lovely aroma of toasted grain, pine, ripening citrus, mango, orange. Medium sweet flavor with further lightly toasted, grainy bread, hints of toasted caramel, oily and lightly bitter pine, orange rind, a little alcohol, earth, mango, papaya. Medium bodied with average carbonation. Resinous and lightly warming on the finish, with earthy bitterness, some light toasty grass, more grains, a little spicy rye, brown bread, rindy citrus. Quite moreish. Really well balanced, yet still robust. Great stuff.
Draft at brewdog birmingham. My new favourite beer. Such a subtle burst of hops. Just wow.
From can, at home! Pours russet brown, with a nice foamy head. Moderate carbonation. Very very drinkable, belying its abv. Toast, nuts, pepper, toffee. Liking this a lot. Please add to core range!

Keg at Brewdog Birmingham; dark copper/red pour with a creamy beige head, aroma has intense pine and some caramel, taste has pine, tangerine, some spice, a hint of caramel, nutty toffee, quite pleasant.

Keg at BD Sheps Bush. It pours clear deep red - brown with a thick off-white head. The nose is bitter - sweet, cherry cola, resinous, brown bread, fruit cake, rum & raisin and toast. The taste is bitter, spicy, woody, resinous, earth, burnt toffee, mild astringency, orange peel, toasted nut and a touch of alcohol with a dry finish. Medium body and moderate carbonation. Decent, but it doesn¬ít blow me away. I¬ím not quite sold on the balance of flavours. I will revisit in due course.
Draught at BrewDog Leicester. Toffee notes with hints of grapefruit in the nose. Full flavoured and very quafable. Definitely in my top 5 beers. Excellent addition to the range.

Keg at Brewdog Shep¬ís bush. Deep reddy amber brown coloured pour with a lasting g lasting thin greyish cream coloured head. Aroma is strawberry jam on toast, figgy, smoked pine needles, earthy. Flavour is composed of semi sweet , toasted grains, nutty, brown bread, spicy orange rind, pine, hint of smoke. Palate is semi sweet, highish carbonation, semi drying finish. Frothy. Assertive piney hop bitterness. Hoppy brown or malty IPA.

Keg, Brewdog Leicester. Amber brown with an off white head. Toffee and nutty rye bread with grapefruit. Mineral body with woody pine. Underlying tropical fruit. Peppery booze with, it¬ís gone. Good balance.
Keg at brewdog bar, Sheffield. Clear brown with small white head. Aroma is grapefruit and bright hops. Taste sweet and bitter and crisp. Mild carb and medium body. Really great beer.

Rich clear sunset auburn, from but the sandy ringed head. Nose is earthy seeded bread crusts, hungry sweetness and a bit of Cola and lime. Initial taste is a rich, dankish coppery bitter with soft pineapple juice before a clean toffee wrap. Carbonation is firm and mouthfeel is gummy. Finishes fairly hefty spicy choc and a swarm of nice dewy caramel finish. It¬ís a bit high end on the juiciness for the backboard of maltiness involved but solid enough. Keg, Brewdog Glasgow
